ong value for a Canadian no-deposit offer.\n    Bonuses requiring 50x+ wagering are typically low-value unless paired with unusually high rewards.\n  </p>\n\n  <!-- Q6 -->\n  <h3>How can I tell if a no deposit bonus is fake?</h3>\n  <p><strong>Look for these red flags:</strong></p>\n  <ul>\n    <li>Landing pages that redirect multiple times through unfamiliar domains.</li>\n    <li>No HTTPS or security certificate.</li>\n    <li>\u201cToo good to be true\u201d offers (e.g., 300\u2013500 free spins, no deposit).</li>\n    <li>Fake or unclickable licensing logos.</li>\n    <li>Crypto-only withdrawals for no-deposit winnings.</li>\n    <li>Support agents who avoid answering basic questions.</li>\n  </ul>\n  <p>\n    If you see any of these signs, avoid the site \u2014 it\u2019s almost certainly a fake\n    or extremely low-quality operator.\n  </p>\n\n  <!-- Q7 -->\n  <h3>What\u2019s the typical max cashout for a no deposit bonus?</h3>\n  <p><strong>Usually C$50\u2013C$200 for Canadian players.</strong></p>\n  <p>\n    Some casinos may increase this limit for fully verified accounts, but\n    <strong>C$100</strong> is the industry standard across most legitimate Canadian no-deposit offers.\n  </p>\n\n  <!-- Q8 -->\n  <h3>Do no deposit bonuses work on all games?</h3>\n  <p><strong>No \u2014 they are almost always limited to specific slots.</strong></p>\n  <p>\n    Free spins from a no-deposit bonus are usually locked to one featured slot or a small group of approved titles\n    to ensure fairness and transparent payout auditing.\n  </p>\n\n  <!-- Q9 -->\n  <h3>Can I claim multiple no deposit bonuses from the same casino?</h3>\n  <p><strong>No \u2014 only one no-deposit bonus per player, household or IP address.</strong></p>\n  <p>\n    Casinos use this rule to prevent abuse. Attempting to bypass it will result in\n    voided winnings and blocked account access across all linked accounts.\n  </p>\n\n  <!-- Q10 -->\n  <h3>Why do some Canadian casinos reject Interac withdr